      review:
        "Your lie in April, a childhood trauma healed by love. I don't think it's worth describing the story of Your Lie in April, as it's well known and appreciated by the majority of the anime community. To put it simply, yes, it's sublime. In terms of visuals, the work is on the whole fairly classic, but it does feature a few performances, notably in the final musical scenes. Yes, this is a work of romance, but don't expect a classic storyline that doesn't dare to say they love each other for 13 episodes, only to reach episode 24 at the first kiss. It's quite clearthat the story's 2 protagonists love each other, but their love develops through their love of music. Some might consider the middle of the piece a bit pointless. I don't consider it dispensable. It's essential to establish the depth of Kousei's relationship with music, a passion tainted by human drama. \nAbove and beyond this romance, which is particularly noticeable at the end of the work, the latter is made special by Kaori's work to heal Kousei's trauma about playing the piano. This journey is completed by the final concert, where Kousei plays for Kaori, her passion and her mother. \n\nYour Lie in April, love is the best medicine.",
