      date: "2023-08-01T18:14:00+00:00",
      review:
        "tl;dr: A manga with a good cast and solid romance, but that drags on too long and feels intentionally frustrating. Nisekoi is a rom-com centered around how the protagonist, Raku, and a girl named Chitoge are forced to date each other despite hating each in order to help calm the conflict between their two families. In a way I guess this is kind of like Romeo and Juliet, in that it features a couple whose respective families hate each other. But I think of it more like a reverse Romeo and Juliet, because instead of the couple wanting to date and the families being against it,the couple doesn’t want to date and the family’s leaders are for it. Instead of trying to hide the fact that they’re in love and meet secretly, they have to hide the fact that they aren’t but having to put on a show of being in love openly.\n\nHowever, in addition to that there’s a plot thread surrounding what happened in Raku’s past. He made a promise with a girl that he was in love with as a kid that when they grew up they would get married, and as proof of that promise Raku got a lock pendant and the girl was given a key. However, he doesn’t remember who that girl was at all and thus is essentially just looking for a girl with the key to his pendent. The thing is that there are multiple girls with keys that remember a promise like that, none of them seem to actually remember who they made the promise with, and furthermore the lock Raku has seems to be broken so they can’t simply use the keys to check.\n\nTo be frank, the plot in the manga was pretty weak. A seemingly core element of the manga is that Raku’s family is yakuza and Chitoge’s family is American mafia which is why the two are in conflict, but that very rarely matters. Early on there’s this thing about how it’s hard for the two to make friends due to their families, but that gets pushed past really quickly. Nothing yakuza or mafia related ever happens. There are supposed assassins but they never assassinate anyone. Eventually a girl connected to the police force and a girl connected to a Chinese triad come in as well. But still, nothing serious happens. Beyond the fact that everyone is super rich, it’s all just aesthetic. It’s actually kind of bizarre how it never plays into anything at all and no one seems to care. Still, I’m fine with manga that aren’t plot focused and rom-coms especially are generally better that way, so while it is disappointing that something that had potential wasn’t used, I don’t see it as a negative.\n\nWhat was a bigger issue is the other core element, the plot line involving the key and lock. While not having a plot I don’t think is a negative, having a bad plot I think certainly is. And while I don’t think the plot is bad necessarily, the way it was told most certainly is. The problem is that is moves incredibly slowly while still constantly being at the forefront. It’s constantly throwing in details that feel like they’re pushing forward in solving the mystery but there’s rarely ever actually any progress. Rather, after it seems like new information is learned, it’ll pretty much always introduce further new information that results in the information previously learned not actually mattering and things being just as mysterious as they were before. It’s frustrating and annoying and wholly unnecessary.\n\nStill, even with the weak plot, the majority of the manga is just the cast living their lives while attending high school so the cast is able to hold up the manga pretty well. Raku is dense and indecisive, but the manga manages to write him pretty well as a good person that genuinely cares about everyone around him so as far as dense and indecisive protagonists go, he’s a pretty great one. None of the heroines are all that deep, but they all have pretty solid personalities and are all written to be pretty likable, so it’s pretty likely that most readers will end up fond of at least one of them.\n\nThe problem is that though there are definite highs and lows, overall things just get too repetitive. While the cast is all pretty likable, no one has a character arc. There are maybe hints of character development here and there, but not enough to matter much in the grand scheme of things. Furthermore, while the cast are likable, they have a very rigid role in the story and they never really step out of it. They’re always in similar situations which they respond to in similar ways without anything too wild ever happening. It becomes immensely predictable and to a degree dull. A lot of the comedy is also rooted in this, and thus while the comedy is decent enough per se, it too starts feeling repetitive and dull. This may not have been a problem when reading it weekly as it came out, but when binge reading it in around a week, I started to feel burnt out on the whole thing.\n\nStill, the romantic aspect I think was handled decently enough that in the grand scheme of things, the manga came out okay. Half of the heroines don’t have a relationship arc, they’re just in love with Raku from before the manga started and remain in love with him. The other half have relationship arcs, but only one felt like it actually fleshed things out properly and was well written. Still, the manga does manage to write all of them being in love and all that fluffy stuff pretty well so everyone’s story is pretty amusing. The one exception that was especially well written was Chitoge’s relationship arc. While her character doesn’t change much over the course of the series, her development of bonds with the other heroines as well as her bond with Raku is really well written and she’s at the center of a lot of very impactful moments.\n\nThe final stretch to the manga also culminates with a heroine getting picked so I’m sure some will be disappointed that their favorite wasn’t. But although it’s somewhat uncertain for most of the manga, during the final stretch it builds up to the conclusion over time in such a way that it felt really obvious long before it got there and regardless of outcome and was also fair to all of the heroines and hits strong emotional beats with all of them. Thus, I feel it was handled as well it possibly could be and I found it a satisfying conclusion.\n\nThe art I felt was too dull. The quality was decent enough and it could be kind of fun with facial expressions. But just in general even for a manga centered around high school, it just felt too plain and like it was never doing anything interesting or trying to look especially nice. In hindsight I feel that may have been a core part of what led to the manga feeling so repetitive.",
